The shorebirds were unsettled and flushed several times; a fast-flying Merlin caused one of the disturbances. Many shorebirds returned, although some shifted to locations closer to the marsh.

No discernable disturbances. The shorebirds were resting along the shoreline when we first arrived. However, the shorebirds were a bit unsettled later in the survey and flushed a few times without a visible disturbance. Many shorebirds returned, although some flew to the marsh.

A fast-moving pilot boat pushed a big wake on the shoreline, causing the shorebirds to flush and/or shift positions along the beach; most returned. Towards the end of the survey, an ATV patrolling the beach area, caused the shorebirds to flush; most AMOY departed.

AMOY were resting on the shoreline during the observation period except for when the wake of a cargo ship caused the birds to shift positions on the shoreline. Also, the mixed flock of shorebirds flushed twice in the absence of a discernable disturbance. Most shorebirds returned to the shoreline within a few minutes.
